Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 28th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Another =
big week of content over here at Not Boring. It=E2=80=99d be awesome if you=
 could share some of it with a friend or colleague that doesn=E2=80=99t yet=
 know about us.
This week we wrote about Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/25c23526-1b=
f2-42ae-ab1c-9274efe5cbf3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 which you can share with anyone that works in=
 real estate, loves Airbnb, or is planning their next getaway.
We also dropped an episode of Not Boring Founders with Sam Levin, the found=
er of Melonfrost [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9cdff03-92e8-4353-a7cd-38=
51fbb07dd4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] =E2=80=94 which you can share with anyone who finds the idea of using =
evolution and AI to design new organisms as fascinating as we do.
You can of course share this Weekly Dose of Optimism, too!
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Sprig [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/f69e3721-2e73-48d2-badb-6054350a9b6d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Sprig [ https://substack.com/redirect/f69e3721-2e73-48d2-badb-6054350a9b6d?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is the=
 easiest way to collect product feedback, inform product decisions, and inc=
rease your speed of innovation. The world=E2=80=99s best product teams incl=
uding the teams at Notion, Loom, and Robinhood use Sprig=E2=80=99s in-app s=
urveys and concept and usability tests to capture insights from their custo=
mers and build better products.
Every week, at the bottom of this newsletter, I use a Sprig [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/f69e3721-2e73-48d2-badb-6054350a9b6d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] survey to get your feedback=
 -- you click a button to tell me whether you loved or hated the newsletter=
 and write a comment, and Sprig categorizes responses with machine learning=
 so that I can get a quick pulse check.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s what I love about Sprig:
The UX is clean and simple, consumer-grade, and they have 75 templates whic=
h makes getting started so easy
It=E2=80=99s incredibly fast to source participants and launch a survey or =
concept test
As a dashboard junkie, I love watching the results and AI-driven insights r=
oll in in real-time, even, and especially, when the feedback is harsh!
We actually almost stopped publishing this newsletter after edition #11 unt=
il we ran a Sprig Survey and discovered that 95% of you enjoyed reading it=
=E2=80=A6so you can thank Sprig for the Weekly Dose of Optimism!
1)  Innovators Who Immigrate [ https://substack.com/redirect/926dfd6a-1813-=
4b29-8668-04fe5e9146cc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Matt Clancy [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c77969f-65e4-41f7-b773-f55d54e=
9cf0c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for What=E2=80=99s New Under the Sun
Talent is spread equally over the planet, but opportunity is not. Today I w=
ant to look at some papers that try to quantify the costs to science and in=
novation from barriers to immigration. Specifically, let=E2=80=99s look at =
a set of papers on what happens to individuals with the potential to innova=
te when they immigrate versus when they do not.
Clancy=E2=80=99s piece is not an editorial on the benefits of immigration o=
r one of those =E2=80=9CDid you know Google, Apple, Amazon, and Facebook we=
re all founded by first or second generation immigrant? [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/172e60b5-c45b-4eee-b55d-4db45c94a90d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D articles. It=E2=80=99s=
 a Substack-style metanalysis on existing papers observing the impact of im=
migration on scientific research and innovation.=20
Some of the more interesting findings:
On average, a migrant is about twice as likely to be employed in academia a=
s a mathematician as someone from the same county who got the same math sco=
re but did not migrate. (Agrawal et al (2023 [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/9f44aefd-b1b1-410f-9d5b-a40bfcd04a73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]))
Leaving the USA due to Fulbright requirements is associated with about 65% =
fewer publications and fewer citations received, and nearly 80% fewer publi=
cations in high-impact journals. (Kahn and MacGarvie (2016) [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/553a7c37-0a2d-4281-8285-0243b9361968?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
After a few years of adjustment, those who returned (to China) start publis=
hing more than their peers who stayed abroad, with this increase concentrat=
ed in last-authored publications (Shi, Liu, and Wang (2023) [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/cc354e4a-bf77-476e-89a7-19ad78f3ecb3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
The big idea, I think, that Clancy is getting to (and is evidenced in the r=
esearch he selected) is that it=E2=80=99s not the act of migrating that is =
good for innovation, but rather migrating to a specific place that=E2=80=99=
s good for innovation. America has been a hotbed of innovation and scientif=
ic research for over a century, not just because of historically high immig=
ration rates, but because it=E2=80=99s established a strong foundation for =
immigrants to pursue such feats upon landing here. Opportunity + People =3D=
 Innovation.=20
2) Spotify founder Daniel Ek officially launches new startup =E2=80=94 and =
this time, he=E2=80=99s taking on healthcare [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/7c15190b-513c-4236-9c54-a41f99797032?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mimi Billing [ https://substack.com/redirect/c73b2cce-8040-44dc-accb-2bdae3=
1e6957?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Sifted
Spotify founder and CEO Daniel Ek is launching a new startup which aims to =
shake up an industry even bigger than music: healthcare. Neko Health will o=
ffer advanced full-body scanning to help doctors find and prevent disease. =
It=E2=80=99s launching after four years of research and development =E2=80=
=94 and hopes to be a gamechanger for Europe=E2=80=99s beleaguered healthca=
re systems.
Speaking of geography and innovation, Daniel Ek=E2=80=94the Swedish founder=
 of Spotify=E2=80=94has pledged over $1B of his own money to backing deepte=
ch companies from Europe [ https://substack.com/redirect/7bd7b0e2-165e-4535=
-ae12-d69fea3fbf6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]. Yesterday, Ek officially launched one of the moonshot compani=
es he funded: Neko Health. The startup will offer advanced full-body scanni=
ng to help doctors find and prevent disease.
Neko is tackling this problem in Europe. In the U.S., companies like Ezra [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/e2cb0861-ddd5-4eb7-889e-f856039ebbc0?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are taking a =
very similar approach to cancer detection. In both health systems, doctors =
are often not given the resources needed to detect and prevent diseases fro=
m progressing until it=E2=80=99s too late, leading to ballooning costs and =
relatively low cure-rates.
Technology isn=E2=80=99t a silver bullet here, but detection can help, and =
making it affordable to more people could lead to better outcomes at lower =
costs. A founder we recently spoke with surprised us when he said, =E2=80=
=9CThere is already a cure for cancer. It=E2=80=99s early detection.=E2=80=
=9D We=E2=80=99re excited to see how this early-detection and preventative =
care space develops over the coming years.=20
3) My Ordinary Life: Improvements Since the 1990s [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/f1a5b45f-5d53-433c-a50d-ad9ffd82a1d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gwern [ https://substack.com/redirect/32d29525-5153-4943-9ed9-60b440dcd238?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for Gw=
ern.net
It can be hard to see the gradual im=E2=81=A3prove=E2=81=A3ment of most goo=
ds over time, but I think one way to get a han=E2=81=A3dle on them is to lo=
ok at their downstream effects: all the small or=E2=81=A3di=E2=81=A3nary ev=
ery=E2=81=A3day things which nev=E2=81=A3er=E2=81=A3the=E2=81=A3less de=E2=
=81=A3pend on ob=E2=81=A3scure in=E2=81=A3no=E2=81=A3va=E2=81=A3tions and i=
m=E2=81=A3prov=E2=81=A3ing cost-=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8Bperformance ra=E2=81=A3ti=
os and grad=E2=81=A3u=E2=81=A3ally drop=E2=81=A3ping costs and new ma=E2=81=
=A3te=E2=81=A3r=E2=81=A3ial and=E2=80=A6 etc. All of these grad=E2=81=A3u=
=E2=81=A3ally drop the cost, drop the price, im=E2=81=A3prove the qual=E2=
=81=A3ity at the same price, re=E2=81=A3move ir=E2=81=A3ri=E2=81=A3ta=E2=81=
=A3tions or lim=E2=81=A3its not ex=E2=81=A3plic=E2=81=A3itly no=E2=81=A3tic=
ed, or so on.
If you could perfectly encapsulate the exact opposite vibe of the one we=E2=
=80=99re going for here at the Weekly Dose op Optimism, it would be that tw=
eet from QC. We could share all of the graphs and stats that show just how =
much progress has occurred and how much the quality of life has risen over =
the past 100 (or even 33) years. But our guess is that that those type of e=
conomics-style arguments aren=E2=80=99t going to change the minds of folks =
like QC. We need real-world examples of how the world has improved. That=E2=
=80=99s where Gwern comes in. The whole list, shared by @yashkaf [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/c829f81c-2d35-46a2-ac61-83a34bb91a9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in QC=E2=80=99s replie=
s, is worth a read, but sharing some of our favorite (non-obvious, and less=
 serious) ones below:
Universal Cables: USB [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f3725d8-415b-48c3-b2=
1d-71226578e128?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] cables mean that for connecting or recharging, we now only need t=
o figure out ~10 different plugs instead of 1000+ (one for every pairwise d=
evice combo)
Movie Theater Seats have become far more comfortable as movie theaters, for=
ced to compete with DVDs/=E2=80=8Bhome-theaters & Internet & video games, u=
pgraded. (We=E2=80=99re particularly big fans of Alamo Drafthouse here at N=
ot Boring)
Ethernet: not needing to know the difference between PLIP, SLIP, IRQ, TCP/=
=E2=80=8BIP, or PPP to get online.
Wheeled Luggage [ https://substack.com/redirect/223ae33e-3595-4fba-9503-723=
7e75219ea?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] no longer expensive or rare, but cheap & ubiquitous. s/o my first real =
job at Away [ https://substack.com/redirect/8238b8a5-d43d-4b44-8859-4a789e7=
6c17c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Better Brussels Sprouts: Brussels sprouts [ https://substack.com/redirect/d=
0664555-239d-4ed7-a102-0b4b1b3e1faf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] no longer taste [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/c811f54c-f6fe-425e-8fb8-14a51b8bffbd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] quite so bad [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/c04f2176-6cbe-49da-a6c7-7872e72ed94d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] due to artificial selection against the =
glucosinolates [ https://substack.com/redirect/db8d65b7-4a8b-443b-ad65-bedc=
b28882b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ].
There are other, more serious improvements cited in the essay as well. Some=
 are the result of technological progress, others the result of regulatory =
change. However you cut it, life has gotten much better of the past 30 year=
s. The world isn=E2=80=99t perfect, but we=E2=80=99re certainly on an upwar=
ds slope.
Side note: I think part of QC=E2=80=99s confusion comes from the fact that =
being a kid rocks.=20
4) Mercedes Claims to Have Achieved Level 3 Automation, Beating Tesla [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/cb1024f5-b198-449d-a5be-e4f095df69b7?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Victor Tangermann [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a0e2597-3cc5-4efd-bd51-5=
676c2a96174?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for Futurism
German automaker Mercedes-Benz claims to have achieved [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/ad90bf0d-f0af-4b7f-ba6a-16807b13aeeb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Level 3 autonomy =E2=80=94 "cond=
itionally automated" vehicles that can monitor their driving environment an=
d make informed decisions on behalf of the driver, but still require humans=
 to occasionally take over =E2=80=94 in the United States, an incremental b=
ut noteworthy step towards a future void of steering wheels [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/41decdc9-296b-44fc-936e-bad147a87dbf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and foot pedals.
Speaking of progress and technological innovation improving quality of life=
, Mercedes-Benz claims to have achieved Level 3 autonomy, certified for U.S=
=2E market usage. Level 3 Autonomy is one=
-level above Tesla=E2=80=99s Level 2=
 Autopilot driver assistance, with the main difference being that drivers d=
on't strictly have to keep their eyes on the road at all times. This level =
of autonomy could free up, or at least relax, close to 100 billion driving =
hours in the US each year. We=E2=80=99re still far off from that, but we=E2=
=80=99re getting incrementally closer both in terms of technological capabi=
lity and deployment of cars that=E2=80=99ll use this technology.
In other car news:
The cost of >300 mile range EVs has plummeted and the number of models offe=
r by different car makers has tripled=E2=80=A6just in the last year. Tesla =
did most of the leg work here, proving out feasibility and market demand, b=
ut now every automaker is introducing compelling EVs.
Both the self-driving story and the EV story are perfect examples of the 4-=
Minute Mile Effect. A feat is impossible until someone shows that it isn=E2=
=80=99t.=20
If you believe in the Tim Urban theory of Elon Musk [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/c7bc6ca4-13d3-4b20-92ec-bc76d407b5f6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], this is all part of the plan.=20
5) A 3D Printer Isn=E2=80=99t Cool. You Know What=E2=80=99s Cool? A 3D-Prin=
ting Factory [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6544c24-751f-4195-ae60-a9ef6e=
38dced?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance [ https://substack.com/redirect/2be5237a-9bb8-4a0e-adaf-6a8a29=
e0ad28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Bloomberg Businessweek
Instead of trying to build a single machine that can print three-dimensiona=
l objects, Freeform is looking to turn entire buildings into automated 3D-p=
rinting factories that would use dozens of lasers to create rocket engine c=
hambers or car parts from metal powder. The company, which has never before=
 discussed its approach publicly, says the technique could allow it to make=
 metal parts 25 to 50 times faster than is possible with current methods an=
d at a fraction of the cost.
IT=E2=80=99S TIME TO PRINT, or something.=20
Ashlee Vance =E2=80=94 of Musk biography fame =E2=80=94 profiled a former S=
paceX engineer=E2=80=99s futuristic 3D printing startup. The startup, Freef=
orm, promises to produce rocket and car parts 25-50x faster and at a fracti=
on of the cost. This has been the general promise of industrial 3D printing=
 for years: cheaper, faster, and often times higher quality. There are, to =
be certain, companies and startups using 3D printing to that end (notably, =
SpaceX) but the promise of ubiquitous 3D printing still seems somewhat far =
off.
Space, however, seems to be one of the more promising industries for 3D pri=
nting. There are customers (NASA, SpaceX, Boeing etc) and a growing number =
of startups competing to disrupt those customers=E2=80=99 historic supply c=
hains, like Freeform, Hadrian [ https://substack.com/redirect/a2a09ca2-b828=
-4040-b5f0-5f927ad918e5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and others.
Whether it starting with 3D printing rocket parts or not, it seems that man=
ufacturing is slowly but surely coming back to America. Atoms are getting s=
exy again. That=E2=80=99s something we support and can be optimistic about.
Did you enjoy reading this Weekly Dose of Optimism?
Yes [ https://substack.com/redirect/b24a7891-8aac-4a23-8910-4e0b2b685945?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] | Meh [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/b24a7891-8aac-4a23-8910-4e0b2b685945?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] | No [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/b24a7891-8aac-4a23-8910-4e0b2b685945?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Powered by Sprig)
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Mo=
nday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

